<head ><bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0014.tlg013' type='cts-urn'>Dem. 13</bibl></head><p > (<name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name>, <title >On Organization</title>; see also <name  n='oratory' type='ancientGenre'>Oratory</name>). This speech was delivered before the <term  sortKey='Assembly'>Assembly</term> at <placeName  key='Athens'>Athens</placeName>, some time after <date  when='-0351'>351 BCE</date> (at <bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0014.tlg013:8' type='cts-urn'>Dem. 13.8</bibl> we learn that the speech was written after the democracy on the island of <placeName  key='Rhodes'>Rhodes</placeName> was overthrown, which happened in <date  when='-0351'>351</date>. Source for date: <bibl >J.H. Vince, <title >Demosthenes I</title> [Cambridge, Mass.; Loeb Classical Library; 1930] 352</bibl>). Nowhere in the speech does the speaker say what, precisely, is the issue before the <term  sortKey='Assembly'>Assembly</term>, and the speech argues several points about government, one after another, generally urging the citizens of <placeName  key='Athens'>Athens</placeName> to take part in the city’s affairs and to avoid apathy, otherwise <placeName  key='Athens'>Athens</placeName> will no longer be a leader among the Greek states. This speech is included in the body of <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name>’ <name  n='oratory' type='ancientGenre'>Oratory</name>, but it is entirely possible that he did not write it. </p>
<byline >Christopher Blackwell</byline>
